Today I implemented a classic and powerful method in Linked Lists â€“ the reverse() function ğŸ”ğŸ’¡

ğŸ”„ What does reverse() do?
It reverses the direction of a Linked List so that the head becomes the tail and vice versa â€” all done in-place, without using extra memory.

ğŸ’» Hereâ€™s the code:
js
Copy
Edit
reverse(){
    let prev = null;
    let curr = this.head;
    while(curr){
        let next = curr.next;
        curr.next = prev;
        prev = curr;
        curr = next;
    }
    this.head = prev;
}
ğŸš€ How it works:
Traverse the list while flipping the direction of each node's .next pointer.

Track the prev node so each node can point backward.

Finally, update the head to point to the last node (now the first).

âœ… Example in action:
js
